&gt; As I described before, sites are responsible for describing (and/or
&gt; having) mail delivery and/or forwarding machines for mail destined for
&gt; their site.  When mail is directed at a machine that doesn't support
&gt; mail (e.g., when somebody reverses a physical return path), the mailers
&gt; described by the machine's site take responsibility for the mail.

David,

    Your definition of sites is fine -- it is analogous to what mine is.
(Apparently I wasn't clear in the past).

    The problem is that even at the fine-grained level you describe,
*sites are not always completely networked internally*.  In other
words, there are sites where different machines within a single
logical site get their mail and connectivity from different networks,
and those machines do not communicate internally.  (I can tell a story
about one such site where the administrators of the BITNET and CSNET
hosts meet once a week to exchange tapes of their mail).

    You cannot assume that by finding out what site a machine is in,
that you know how to deliver to it.

Craig

